In [[physics]], the term '''Pouillet effect''' refers to an [[exothermic reaction]] that takes place when a liquid is added to a powder. It was first observed by [[John Leslie (physicist)|Leslie]] in 1802 when dry sawdust was wetted with water.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Leslie|first1=John|title=On capillary action|journal=Philosophical Magazine|date=1802|volume=14|pages=193–205|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=pst.000068484644;view=1up;seq=205|series=1st series}} From p. 201: Upon wetting paper or linen with water or oil, and " … applying a delicate thermometer, I perceived a very sensible extrication of heat invariably to take place during such combinations. And this effect was the greater in proportion to the previous dryness of the solid. Thus I have sometimes produced a heat of ten degrees by moistening saw-dust which had been parched before the fire."</ref> [[Claude Pouillet]] later described this phenomenon in 1822 when it came to be known as the '''Pouillet effect''' in France.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Pouillet|title=Mémoire sur de nouveaux phénomènes de production de chaleur|journal=Annales de Chimie et de Physique|date=1822|volume=20|pages=141–162|series=2nd series|trans-title=Memoir on new phenomena of heat production|language=French}} From p. 142: ''"À l'instant où un liquide mouille un solide, il y a dégagement de chaleur."'' (At the instant when a liquid wets a solid, there is a release of heat.)</ref><ref name="Pouillet Effect">'Adsorption by powders & porous solids: principles, methodology and applications' Academic Press, 1999.</ref>
